Here's a simple JavaScript `debounce` function with an example:

The `debounce` function delays the execution of a given function until a specified time has passed without further calls.

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeoutId;

  return function(...args) {
    if (timeoutId) {
      clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    }
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
      func.apply(this, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}

// Example usage:
const sayHello = () => {
  console.log("Hello!");
};

const debouncedSayHello = debounce(sayHello, 300);
debouncedSayHello(); // No output
debouncedSayHello(); // No output
// After 300ms, "Hello!" will be logged once
```

In this example, `debouncedSayHello` is a debounced version of `sayHello` with a 300ms delay. Even though `debouncedSayHello` is called twice in quick succession, `sayHello` will only be executed once after 300ms have passed without any additional calls.
